T1  - Portfolio Selection with Capital Gains Tax, Recursive Utility, and Regime Switching
AU  - Cai, Jiatu
AU  - Chen, Xinfu
AU  - Dai, Min
Y1  - 2017/03/02
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2018/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2650
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2650
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2308
EP  - 2324
VL  - 64
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Capital gains taxation has important implications for investors? portfolio choice decisions. To explore these implications, we develop a continuous time investment and consumption model with capital gains tax, Epstein?Zin recursive utility, and regime switching. We find that various factors, such as tax rate, risk aversion, interest rate, stock return, and volatility, jointly affect optimal portfolio allocation, whereas intertemporal substitution does not. In a regime switching market, investors may trade or stop trading purely because of a change in regime, and there is a distinct cross-regime effect on optimal portfolio allocation. In particular, investors tend to raise stock investment in a bear regime so as to reduce potential tax payments upon regime switching. Given reasonable parameter values, regime switching has a greater impact on optimal portfolio allocation in a bear regime than in a bull regime. This paper was accepted by Neng Wang, finance.
AB  - Capital gains taxation has important implications for investors? portfolio choice decisions. To explore these implications, we develop a continuous time investment and consumption model with capital gains tax, Epstein?Zin recursive utility, and regime switching. We find that various factors, such as tax rate, risk aversion, interest rate, stock return, and volatility, jointly affect optimal portfolio allocation, whereas intertemporal substitution does not. In a regime switching market, investors may trade or stop trading purely because of a change in regime, and there is a distinct cross-regime effect on optimal portfolio allocation. In particular, investors tend to raise stock investment in a bear regime so as to reduce potential tax payments upon regime switching. Given reasonable parameter values, regime switching has a greater impact on optimal portfolio allocation in a bear regime than in a bull regime. This paper was accepted by Neng Wang, finance.
